The Cathedral of the Violet Eclipse sits along the western approaches from Midgaard toward the Roc Road — close enough for city supply from magistrate-approved stonewrights, far enough outside Watch circuits for deniable reliquary work.
It began as the Violet Arch Chapel-House, a Violet Compact era reliquary checkpoint with three civic duties: threshold adjudication for relic-bearing caravans, ritual quarantine for artifacts that could not enter Midgaard without classification, and archive relay where oaths and custody manifests were copied and forwarded to the Magistrate Ledgerhouse.
In this founding era, violet pigments and amethyst lanterns were administrative markers, not occult symbols. They indicated Compact jurisdiction, just as the Violet Reliquary Arch at Midgaard's civic core uses violet lacquer as functional registry checkpoint markers.
The Silenced Vespers: reform clerks attempted to publish contradictory ledgers proving high-born petitioners received absolution while bonded laborers were condemned under identical evidence. Before those records reached public dockets, bell-lines inside the chapel-house went silent. Outer doors were sealed. The institution declared itself "withdrawn into eclipse until judgment ripens."
The Fivefold Occlusion is the doctrine's core litany: Color reveals rank. Rank determines witness. Witness determines memory. Memory determines sentence. Sentence determines who may be named.
Five institutional wings: Processional Court (Central Spine — intake rites and sentence theater), Sanguine Choir (Crimson Wing — confession extraction, blood oath enforcement, musical legal instruments), Violet Reliquary (Amethyst Wing — relic custody brokering legitimacy), Obsidian Scriptoria (Ink Wing — record fabrication, null-seal issuance), Moonbone Ossuary (Silver Wing — funerary conversion, posthumous jurisdiction).
The eclipse doctrine inverted Kel'Shadra's triune witness formula: witness what is true became witness what authority permits; offer what is owed became withhold what is inconvenient; bind what must endure became bind what serves continuity.
Among the archive relay duties the chapel-house performed: processing sealed warrants that condemned debtors and petty criminals to labor service, including transfers to the Spirebound Conclave. The institution took its copy of those transit ledgers when it withdrew into eclipse — records the Reckoning Faction has sought for generations.
The null-seal is the cathedral's most feared administrative power: a wax impression in obsidian-tinted material that renders a document's contents officially nonexistent while leaving the physical artifact intact as a monument to institutional authority.
Thornwood timber was selectively procured for confession codices and null-sealed precedent volumes, valued for anomalous density and preservative compounds. Later procurement records use vague geographic references for identical grade specifications, documenting the shift from open trade to deniable procurement after Thornwood's exclusion classification.
The cathedral is not merely a corrupted religious institution; it is a living archive of Midgaard's institutional crimes, sealed behind doctrinal walls and defended by a clergy that built a theology around the right to control what records survive.
Color in the cathedral is jurisdictional metadata made sacred: violet is authority, crimson is coercion, indigo is archive, obsidian is erasure, silver is finality, gold is exceptional decrees from the Hierophant's throne.

